title: Change the head of the "Gatta di Sant'Andrea!"

description.text:
There are the results of the 3DiTALY contest "PADOVA: mettici la faccia!". Participants had to imagine the head of the Paduan medieval sculpture called Gatta di Sant'Andrea (Cat of S. Andrea).
This headless sculpture is located in the centre of the city of Padua, in Northern Italy.

http://www.padovaoggi.it/eventi/padova-mettici-la-faccia-contest-gatta-vicolo-sant-andrea-padova.html

http://www.3ditaly.it/contest-gatta/

The winners:

The front view of this head reminds a Sci-Fi cat (the present and the future of Padua). The lateral view reminds a profile of lion, the original medieval figure (the past of Padua).

http://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gatta_di_Sant'Andrea

This sculpture has fallen and has been rebuilt many times in the story of the city. This head represents this concept: reconstructing fragments in a mosaic.

http://mattinopadova.gelocal.it/padova/cronaca/2015/03/19/news/un-anno-e-mezzo-dopo-la-gatta-di-padova-e-tornata-a-sant-andrea-1.11075744

This head is an ironic joke, an hybrid between a cat and the famous Paduan chicken breed.

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Padovana_chicken

title: Folding Prop ( Propeller ) for RC planes, gliders
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
After several crashes, I was out of replacement props so I decided to print my own!
The ones available on the internet were either badly designed or just wouldn't work for me, so I started remodelling my own, broken propeller. And the result, after hours of finetuning and reshaping, is here!
In total 16 different versions have been made.. The plane this was designed for is the phoenix 2000 or phoenix evolution. TIPS and RECOMMENDATIONS:
  • This is a high torque propeller! Be sure to use a low KV motor otherwise it might overheat. (Happened to me once - no fun)
  • Try to print the propeller upwards (standing), it will give the best results
  • I used PLA with a 4mm nozzle, 0.2mm layer height, but ABS might even be better due to it's flexibility.
  • Props might need balancing after printing! Not checking this might cause serious deformation of the motor's shaft and eventually break down.
    • Hole size: +/- 3 mm
    Hub size: +/- 8 mm I have included the .blend file so you can edit it to suit your own needs. Good luck!

comments.text:
Thanks for your comment. You're right about the centrigufal force and direction of the grain, printing it laying down would result in a stronger part. However, it would also require a minimal layer height (0.1 mm or less) to achieve the same quality of details (the curve of the blade), and support material is defenitely needed (which is hard to remove without leaving damage for some people).
I guess everyone should decide for theirselves what option is best for his/her case.

title: Rostock Max Low Profile Fan Remix

description.text:
Recently added an E3D V6 hotend to my Rostock Max.  Tried a couple of different layer fan replacements, but had some problems with them interfering either with the arms or with the heads of the modified bolts I'm using.  Started wondering if I could remix one of the designs into something that would work for me, and this is the result.  
dreyfusduke's design relies on having the effector platform upside down (apparently for LED mounting), but mine is right side up, so the mounting tab is ~5.5mm higher for me.  I sliced his vertical section, slid it up, and duplicated part of it.  The result has two mounting slots, so you can use it for either orientation of your effector platform.  
NOTE: I'm in the middle of another print right now, so this is currently untested.  The additional vertical height was a rough measurement, and may not be enough.  The OpenSCAD file is available if you need to tweak.  It relies on having dreyfusduke's "part3.stl" in the same directory.  
FINAL RESULT:  Ugh.  I'm using a stand/mount for the E3D V6 hotend that holds it pretty high, so there is very little clearance under the effector table.  I've modified this part so that it is as tight to the effector table as I can get it, and it still drags the table.  Thinking about it now, I'm not sure if there is enough room for any layer fan duct design...  I'll leave this here in case it is useful for someone else.

Should print without supports, as long as you can handle short bridges (up to maybe 15mm).  
Like most layer fan shrouds, the end of this will be very close to the hot end.  I printed mine in ABS for better heat tolerance, just to be safe.

comments.text: I'm a programmer by nature, so the text/programming process of OpenSCAD is easier for me to repeatedly tweak than most of the other CAD programs I'm familiar with.  Inside OpenSCAD, I imported the original STL into three copies (though now that I think about it, it should only be two, so that's what I'll describe).  I used a boolean difference with a cube to cut the top off of one, and the same to cut the bottom off the other, and then aligned the two parts for the distance I wanted between the mounting slots.  I would imagine most other tools could do the same fairly easily.

I also used m3 hex head bolts around 8mm long to build the frame, I've included the 35mm spacer just duplicate it for your needs.

title: Bed Leveller Mini Kossel / Delta RichRap

description.text:
My first upload to so please critic away....  
I purchased my first 3D print from a really helpful guy in Oxfordshire (mentioning no names... Greg!). Assembled this over the next few weeks with a lot of help from Greg but tweaked the assembly to my only liking. Once it was assembled I was just over the moon with my first print of a skull without support that I watched the whole 3 hour print.  
One of the first things to tackle was the main issue of bed levelling. Having read all the forum, asked many people and lots of thinking i decided the best thing to do was to make a means of manual adjust using simple nuts and screws.  
What I thought would be a simple task turned out to many many redesigns and tweak and I learnt a lot in regards to tolerances and limitations of 3D printing with my particular printer. It also reminded me how badly I needed bed levelling LOL  
Anyway I've attached a exploded view of the parts required and I would say the hardest thing for me was finding a spring. You may fair better than me but look for a retractable pen spring that has a internal bore of 5mm  
This is my first upload so love to see your prints and feedback I'll be also uploading my arduino RAMPS case for this printer as well

Parts required (sets of 3)
3x M5x50mm Machine screw (Pan Head, button head or Cap head will do)
12x M5 Washers
9x M5 Half washer
3x Spring 25mm long with internal bore of >5.5mm Assembly
  • There would be three existing wholes on the bed which should measure approximatly 153.5mm apart. Drill these to give 5mm clearance holes. If you don't have these wholes simply measure the diameter of your glass bed and using a vector based program (123design or Adobe Illustrator) plot out the arrangement of the layout of your bed and the three holes required. from the perimeter of the glass bed you measured you'll need a distance of 16mm
  • Place an M5 washer on the M5 Machine screw and insert into the M5 hole from the underside
  • Place another M5 washer followed with a M5 half nut and screw this down tightly so that you now have three threaded rods sticking up out of the bed base
  • Using another half M5 nut insert this into the Adjuster wheel. It is paramount that this be inserted completing flat so that the its axis it perpindicular to the adjuster wheel. Failing to do this will give you a wobble when adjusting. TOP TIP: using another M5 machine screw, thread on an M5 nut with a M5 Washer and another M5 nut and tighten this to the very end of the screw. Heat up the end nut with a lighter and then insert it. This way the washer will act as a guide giving you a level insertion of the nut and the heat will bond the plastic to the nut (see pics for reference)
  • screw your Adjuster wheel onto the threaded rods
  • Insert the Bed Holder
  • insert the Bed Holder Top
  • Slot in your Glass Bed
  • Insert an M5 Washer
  • Insert the springs
  • Insert an M5 washer
  • Screw on an M5 Nut and tighten this up about 5mm down or until you feel the bed is stable and tight.
  • Your finished
    • Operational Instructions
    Simply adjust the thumbwheel in the positive or negative direction will bring the bed up or down.
    My advice is to print a ring about 150mm in diameter and 5mm with on a very slow print so that you can adjust the bed accorgingly.
    Once your setup and happy with the adjustment you just need to come back and slightly tweak the adjustment wheel 1/8th of a turn either way.
    On every print I would also recommend you add a skirt 6mm from the object that give you minimum 3 loops which should be sufficient for you to make those tweaks

description.text: This is a cookie cutter for making Pacman-shaped cookies.

Created with this process: Use this Processing app to edit or create your cookie cutter pattern: http://www.local-guru.net/blog/pages/cookiecutter-editor If you want to use this particular model as an example, the source file is:
pacman-cookiecutter-source-file This tool can export to .stl files. Cookies with this process: Use a sugar cookie recipe, cut out using this pattern, and decorate to your heart's content! Flatten the dough into a large flat area about the same height as the cutter. We found using a flat plate helped keeping the height consistent for a large surface area. You could also use another cookie sheet to squish it flat. The larger the surface area, the more cut-outs you can make in one go. Generally the cutter should grab onto and hold the dough with friction. Then you can gently push it out with your finger onto the cookie sheet. We found it easiest to lift the dough off the cutting board when there's some flour on the cutting board. Alternatively, spread the dough directly onto your cookie sheet, use the cutter, then pull away the excess dough. Decorations: Consider chocolate chips for eyes. Consider using decorating cake icing for additional details, like the Ms. Pacman bow. :)

title: Walkera Tali H500 BN-300 GPS Module Spacers

description.text:
If you wan to upgrade the GPS module of your Walkera Tali H500 Hexacopter with the new BN-300 GPS that adds Glonass support you will find that it will not fit on the place of the old GPS module inside the drone's body. The new BN-300 GPS module is slightly bigger, so in order to install it inside the body of the Tali H500 you will need to add spacers. So we have designed exactly that - a spacer to mount the new GPS module inside, you need to print 4 in total and you will also need a bit longer screws than the ones used with the standard module to attach the new one.  
Print using a fine resolution such as 0.1mm and do enable support to get the best results, it should fit very nice if printed with PLA filament.With these spacers there is no need to use an external case for the GPS module like on the Walkera Scout X4, though the alternative solution to using the spacers is exactly that...

description.text:
This is a cookie cutter for making Pacman Ghost-shaped cookies.
(Ghosts in the game Pacman are also called Gremlins.  The more you know!)

Cutter created with this process: Use this Processing app to edit or create your cookie cutter pattern: local-guru.net/blog/pages/cookiecutter-editor If you want to use this particular model as an example, the source file is:
pacman-cookiecutter-source-file This tool can export to .stl files. Cookies with this process: Use a sugar cookie recipe, cut out using this pattern, and decorate to your heart's content! Flatten the dough into a large flat area about the same height as the cutter. We found using a flat plate helped keeping the height consistent for a large surface area. You could also use another cookie sheet to squish it flat. The larger the surface area, the more cut-outs you can make in one go. Generally the cutter should grab onto and hold the dough with friction. Then you can gently push it out with your finger onto the cookie sheet. We found it easiest to lift the dough off the cutting board when there's some flour on the cutting board. Alternatively, spread the dough directly onto your cookie sheet, use the cutter, then pull away the excess dough. Decorations: Consider chocolate chips for eyes. Consider using food colouring to make different coloured ghosts. For best results, when making your dough, use the food colouring on the wet stuff first, before adding the dry stuff (flour etc). The colours won't mix as well after the dry stuff is added. Consider using decorating cake icing for additional details, eyes, eyelashes, etc. :)

description.text:
Handy portable rack for eight reels of wire.  
I have lots of wire in the workshop â€“ when you buy 100m reels it gets cheap. However I never had space to have all of these on the bench at once, Awkward to take with me too, if I was working away from my usual workshop.  
So here's a little rack, and home-made reels to go into it.  About 100' fits on each reel, less for thicker wire
Cable reels

Cut the circular end plates from something thin - I used 2.5mm hardboard.  Then cut lengths of 20mm PVC electrical conduit to make reel cores.  Assemble them with hot melt glue. Try to keep the plates square and the outside end smooth.  
Rack

The rack is laser cut from 6mm MDF. The centre dividers are from the same thin stuff as the cable reels. You can adjust the mortices for either if you change the material thicknesses. Assemble with wood glue and a coat of shellac to keep the damp off.  
NB - the end plates and the dividers have an "Up" direction - the spindle holes are all slightly above the centre line. Make sure you assemble them all the same way round.  
The spindles are just two lengths of 10mm dowel. I located mine side-to-side with a couple of tiny rare-earth magnets and hotmelt. You could use tape, tiewraps or anything.  
If you're using the PDFs, just cut the black lines and ignore the red or blue.
